<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="h2">
      <span class="rule"></span>
      CASE 3
    </div>

    <div class="case-details">
      <h3>Project Title: Queerology</h3>
      <p><strong>Organization / Industry:</strong> Independent Educational Initiative • Public Online Education</p>
      <p><strong>Date:</strong> 2023–2025</p>
      <p><strong>Solution Artifacts:</strong> Queerology Instagram</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Webinar recordings</li>
        <li>Presentation materials</li>
        <li>Reading lists and session outlines</li>
      </ul>

      <h4>Solution Overview</h4>
      <p>Designed a live webinar-based learning format supported by curated academic materials. Sessions combined structured instruction, moderated discussion, and guided meaning-making.</p>

      <h4>Problem Statement</h4>
      <p>A gap existed between academically rigorous queer theory and accessible public education. Available resources were either inaccessible or oversimplified, limiting informed discourse and critical understanding.</p>

      <h4>My Role</h4>
      <p>Instructional Designer • Content Curator • Facilitator • Academic Translator</p>

      <h4>Target Audience</h4>
      <p>Adult learners without formal academic background • Educators, activists, journalists • International audience</p>

      <h4>Stakeholder & SME Alignment</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Collaborated with faculty members and academic practitioners as primary subject matter experts</li>
        <li>Co-developed course content with a colleague acting as SME, working as a small instructional design team rather than a solo designer</li>
        <li>Navigated academic databases and peer-reviewed literature to identify, evaluate, and prioritize high-impact theoretical frameworks</li>
        <li>Synthesized and distilled complex academic research into structured, teachable instructional narratives</li>
        <li>Translated and adapted academic concepts into a target language in which no established academic resources currently exist, effectively creating a foundational reference base for future academic use</li>
        <li>Balanced faculty expectations, theoretical rigor, learner accessibility, and psychological safety through iterative design and facilitation</li>
        <li>Treated learners as key stakeholders, explicitly designing for access, equity, and cognitive load across diverse cultural and educational backgrounds</li>
      </ul>

      <h4>Key Constraints & Challenges</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Translating theory without loss of meaning</li>
        <li>Diverse cultural and knowledge baselines</li>
        <li>Engagement with theory-heavy material</li>
        <li>Psychological safety in sensitive discussions</li>
      </ul>

      <h4>Learning Outcomes</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Academic grounding in gender studies, sociology, psychology</li>
        <li>Scaffolded conceptual progression</li>
        <li>Narrative-based instructional translation</li>
        <li>Interactive reflection and Q&A</li>
        <li>Explicit psychological safety framing</li>
      </ul>

      <h4>Assessment & Evaluation</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Pre/post self-assessment</li>
        <li>Scenario-based final evaluation</li>
        <li>Facilitator observation</li>
        <li>Qualitative participant feedback</li>
      </ul>

      <h4>Results / Impact</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>High live-session engagement</li>
        <li>Strong qualitative feedback on clarity</li>
        <li>Increased learner confidence discussing LGBTQ+ topics</li>
        <li>Repeat attendance across sessions</li>
      </ul>

      <h4>Key Takeaway</h4>
      <p>Demonstrates academic translation and facilitation of complex theory for non-academic audiences.</p>

